  "prompt": "Which knee is best for replacement surgery?",
  "response": "The decision on **which knee** to replace depends on the specific condition and needs of the patient, not on a general preference for the left or right knee. Knee replacement surgery (also called **knee arthroplasty**) is typically recommended for severe arthritis, injury, or damage that causes chronic pain, stiffness, or reduced mobility. Here\u2019s how the decision is made:\n\n### Factors to Consider:\n1. **Severity of Pain and Damage**:\n   - The knee that is more affected by arthritis, injury, or wear and tear is usually the one chosen for replacement.\n\n2. **X-rays and Imaging**:\n   - Imaging tests (like X-rays or MRIs) help determine which knee has more significant cartilage loss, bone damage, or deformity.\n\n3. **Functional Impairment**:\n   - The knee that limits daily activities (e.g., walking, climbing stairs, or standing) more severely is typically prioritized.\n\n4. **Patient Preference**:\n   - The patient\u2019s pain level and quality of life in each knee are considered. Some patients may prefer to address the more painful knee first.\n\n5. **Bilateral Knee Issues**:\n   - If both knees are severely damaged, the worse one is usually addressed first. In some cases, bilateral knee replacement (both knees at once) may be considered, but this depends on the patient\u2019s overall health and surgeon\u2019s recommendation.\n\n### Which Knee Is Replaced Most Often?\nThere\u2019s no significant statistical difference in whether the **left or right knee** is replaced more frequently. It depends entirely on the individual\u2019s condition.\n\n### After Surgery:\nRecovery and rehabilitation are critical. Physical therapy is essential to regain strength and mobility in the replaced knee.\n\n### Consult Your Surgeon:\nThe final decision should be made in consultation with an orthopedic surgeon, who will evaluate your specific condition and recommend the best course of action.",
